Your acceleration is 60km/sec over a year of acceleration, and that's fairly fast, to be sure.<br>
The problem is that's a <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>year</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> of acceleration! Even chemical rockets give you enough to go on your way to Mars and be there in under 9 months.<br>
<br>
Our point is that an NPR ship gets the crew there in <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>vastly</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> less time. While your NEP ship is warming up and pushing slowly towards Earth escape velocity, the NPR ship has gone there, dropped off the payload, taken on a load of water &amp; chemicals from the fledgling factory it delivered, and is on its way home.<br>
 Taking off from Earth, with 33km/sec for free, we thrust for 3 hours, for a interplanetary cruise speed of 58km/sec, which gets the crew there before they've died from complications from long-term space exposure.<br>
<br>
Eventually, we'll grow up past the point of believing everything some hysteria monger spreads &quot;<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> the plutonium will kill everything on Earth!</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->&quot; (when the truth is that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> if</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> there's a launch accident, it'll be recovered with no leakage from the wreckage at the bottom of the ocean) or &quot;<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> It's a military warship in disguise and they want to mind-ray us from orbit!</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->&quot; and we'll pay attention to what's really going on with the mission, what they hope to do with what's going on in space, and what we can gain from sending Pu up there and blowing it off into the solar wind once &amp; for all.<br>
